poetic_form.description: The Monk of Teaching is a light poetic form intended to renounce religion, originating in The Lustrous Basement. The rules of the form are applied by poets to produce individual poems which can be recited. The poem is a single quatrain. Use of assonance, metaphor and juxtaposition is characteristic of the form. The fourth line of the quatrain shares the underlying meaning of the second line. The second line of the quatrain is required to maintain the phrasing of the first line. The first line has six feet with a tone pattern of uneven-even. It has a terminal caesura. The second line has five feet with a tone pattern of uneven-even. It has an initial caesura. The third line must make use of vivid imagery. It has three feet with a tone pattern of uneven-even. It has a terminal caesura. The fourth line has four feet with a tone pattern of uneven-even. It has a terminal caesura. The rhyme scheme of the poem is AAAB.

The Meandering Incense is a poetic narrative, originating in The Lustrous Basement. The rules of the form are applied by poets to produce individual poems which can be recited. The poem is divided into a quatrain and four tercets. Use of metaphor is characteristic of the form. Every line of the poem has a terminal caesura. [B]The first part is intended to describe the past. The fourth line of the quatrain must expand the idea of the second line. It has lines with six syllables. The rhyme scheme respecting the full poem is ABBB. [B]The second part is intended to move away from previous ideas concerning current events. The second line of each tercet must expand the idea of the first line. It has lines with six syllables. The rhyme scheme respecting the full poem is CDD.

musical_form.description: The Adorable Skirt is a devotional form of music originating in The Lustrous Basement. The form guides musicians during improvised performances. The music is played on a kthag. The entire performance should be melancholic and gradually slows as it comes to an end. The melody has short phrases throughout the form. It is performed in the nural rhythm. Throughout, when possible, performers are to modulate frequently. [B]The kthag always does the main melody and is to be very loud. [B]The Adorable Skirt has a well-defined multi-passage structure: a chorus and a verse all repeated two times and a coda. [B]In the chorus, the kthag covers its entire range from the rich low register to the eerie high register. This passage typically has some sparse chords. The passage is performed using the ntak scale. [B]In the verse, the kthag covers its entire range from the rich low register to the eerie high register. This passage features only melodic tones and intervals. The passage is performed using the kulet scale. [B]In the coda, the kthag stays in the eerie high register. Chords are packed close together in dense clusters in this passage. The passage is performed using the ermis scale. [B]Scales are conceived of as two chords built using a division of the perfect fourth interval into eleven notes. The tonic note is a fixed tone passed from teacher to student. Preferred notes in the fundamental scale are named. The names are thoth (spoken tho, 3rd), thatthil (tha, 5th) and gstang (g, 10th). [B]As always, the ntak hexatonic scale is thought of as two disjoint chords drawn from the fundamental division of the perfect fourth. These chords are named anam and emr. [B]The anam trichord is the 1st, the 7th and the 11th degrees of the fundamental perfect fourth division. [B]The emr tetrachord is the 1st, the 5th, the 6th and the 11th degrees of the fundamental perfect fourth division. [B]As always, the kulet hexatonic scale is thought of as two disjoint chords drawn from the fundamental division of the perfect fourth. These chords are named alak and emr. [B]The alak trichord is the 1st, the 10th and the 11th degrees of the fundamental perfect fourth division. [B]As always, the ermis heptatonic scale is thought of as two disjoint chords drawn from the fundamental division of the perfect fourth. These chords are named mabdug and emr. [B]The mabdug tetrachord is the 1st, the 6th, the 9th and the 11th degrees of the fundamental perfect fourth division. [B]The rhythm system is fundamentally polyrhythmic. There are always multiple rhythm lines, and each of their bars is played over the same period of time, regardless of the number of beats. The rhythm lines are thought of as one, without a primary-subordinate relationship, though individual lines can be named. [B]The nural rhythm is made from three patterns: the fer, the olmul and the ugog. As stated above, they are to be played in polyrhythm. [B]The fer rhythm is a single line with four beats. The beats are named uvel (spoken uv), dolush (do), agk (ag) and ucat (uc). The beat is stressed as follows:[B]| x x - x | [B]where x is a beat, - is silent and | indicates a bar. [B]The olmul rhythm is a single line with seven beats. The beat is stressed as follows:[B]| x - x - x x - | [B]where x is a beat, - is silent and | indicates a bar. [B]The ugog rhythm is a single line with two beats. The beats are named ish (spoken ish) and robek (ro). The beat is stressed as follows:[B]| x - | [B]where x is a beat, - is silent and | indicates a bar.

The Lavender Style is a form of music used during marches and military engagements originating in The Lustrous Basement. The rules of the form are applied by composers to produce individual pieces of music which can be performed. A speaker recites nonsensical words and sounds while the music is played on a nitem. The musical voices are joined in melody. The melody has long phrases throughout the form. Never more than an interval sounds at once. It is performed using the tosid scale and in the okag rhythm. Throughout, when possible, composers and performers are to alternate tension and repose and modulate frequently. [B]The speaker always should feel mysterious and is to be very soft. [B]The nitem always does the main melody, should perform sweetly and is to become louder and louder. [B]The Lavender Style has a well-defined multi-passage structure: one to two passages and an additional passage and a finale. [B]Each of the first simple passages slows and broadens. [B]The second simple passage is twice the tempo of the last passage. [B]The finale resumes the original tempo. [B]Scales are conceived of as two chords built using a division of the perfect fourth interval into eleven notes. The tonic note is a fixed tone passed from teacher to student. Preferred notes in the fundamental scale are named. The names are thoth (spoken tho, 3rd), thatthil (tha, 5th) and gstang (g, 10th). [B]As always, the tosid heptatonic scale is thought of as two disjoint chords drawn from the fundamental division of the perfect fourth. These chords are named mabdug and ustos. [B]The mabdug tetrachord is the 1st, the 6th, the 9th and the 11th degrees of the fundamental perfect fourth division. [B]The ustos tetrachord is the 1st, the 4th, the 6th and the 11th degrees of the fundamental perfect fourth division. [B]The rhythm system is fundamentally polyrhythmic. There are always multiple rhythm lines, and each of their bars is played over the same period of time, regardless of the number of beats. The rhythm lines are thought of as one, without a primary-subordinate relationship, though individual lines can be named. [B]The okag rhythm is made from two patterns: the nokzam and the olmul. As stated above, they are to be played in polyrhythm. [B]The nokzam rhythm is a single line with thirty-two beats divided into eight bars in a 4-4-4-4-4-4-4-4 pattern. The beat is stressed as follows:[B]| - x - - | - - x - | - - x x | - x x x | - - x - | - x x - | - - x x | x x - x | [B]where x is a beat, - is silent and | indicates a bar. [B]The olmul rhythm is a single line with seven beats. The beat is stressed as follows:[B]| x - x - x x - | [B]where x is a beat, - is silent and | indicates a bar.

The Chartreuse Rhyme is a form of music used to commemorate important events originating in The Lustrous Basement. The rules of the form are applied by composers to produce individual pieces of music which can be performed. A singer recites any composition of The Monk of Teaching while the music is played on a kudar. The music is melody and rhythm without harmony. The melody has mid-length phrases throughout the form. Only one pitch is ever played at a time. It is performed using the berim scale and in the udir rhythm. Throughout, when possible, composers and performers are to glide from note to note, play arpeggios and match notes and syllables. [B]The singer always does the main melody and is to be very loud. The voice stays in the low register. [B]The kudar always provides the rhythm and is to be loud. [B]The Chartreuse Rhyme has a simple structure: a passage. [B]The simple passage should be jumpy and is moderately fast. The passage should be composed and performed using syncopation. [B]Scales are conceived of as two chords built using a division of the perfect fourth interval into eleven notes. The tonic note is a fixed tone passed from teacher to student. Preferred notes in the fundamental scale are named. The names are thoth (spoken tho, 3rd), thatthil (tha, 5th) and gstang (g, 10th). [B]As always, the berim pentatonic scale is thought of as two disjoint chords drawn from the fundamental division of the perfect fourth. These chords are named alak and zustash. [B]The alak trichord is the 1st, the 10th and the 11th degrees of the fundamental perfect fourth division. [B]The zustash trichord is the 1st, the 5th and the 11th degrees of the fundamental perfect fourth division. [B]The rhythm system is fundamentally polyrhythmic. There are always multiple rhythm lines, and each of their bars is played over the same period of time, regardless of the number of beats. The rhythm lines are thought of as one, without a primary-subordinate relationship, though individual lines can be named. [B]The osmze rhythm is made from two patterns: the zudl and the ugas. The Petals of Glimmering is a form of music used for entertainment originating in The Terrors of Muting. The rules of the form are applied by composers to produce individual pieces of music which can be performed. One to five chanters recite any composition of The Gloss of Insight while the music is played on a smal. The musical voices cover melody, harmony and rhythm. The entire performance is to be in whispered undertones. The melody has phrases of varied length throughout the form. It is performed without preference for a scale. Throughout, when possible, composers and performers are to locally improvise. [B]Each chanter always does the main melody, should be spirited and makes trills. [B]The smal always should stress the rhythm and makes trills. [B]The Petals of Glimmering has a well-defined multi-passage structure: a lengthy theme, an exposition of the theme and a recapitulation of the theme. [B]The theme is voiced by the melody of the chanters and the harmony of the smal. The passage is moderately fast. Each of the chanters' voices covers its entire range. This passage typically has some sparse chords. The passage is performed in the strog rhythm. [B]The exposition is voiced by the melody of the chanters and the rhythm of the smal. The passage is half the tempo of the last passage. Each of the chanters' voices ranges from the low register to the middle register. This passage typically has some sparse chords. The passage is performed in free rhythm. [B]The recapitulation is voiced by the melody of the chanters and the melody of the smal. The passage is moderately fast. Each of the chanters' voices stays in the middle register. This passage is richly layered with full chords making use of the available range. The passage is performed in the ospo rhythm. [B]The rhythm system is fundamentally polyrhythmic. There are always multiple rhythm lines, and each of their bars is played over the same period of time, regardless of the number of beats. The rhythm lines are thought of as one, without a primary-subordinate relationship, though individual lines can be named. [B]The strog rhythm is made from two patterns: the stotho and the stl. As stated above, they are to be played in polyrhythm. [B]The stotho rhythm is a single line with nine beats divided into three bars in a 3-3-3 pattern. The beats are named bor (spoken bo), osm (osm) and enu (en). The beat is stressed as follows:[B]| x x x | x - - | x x x | [B]where x is a beat, - is silent and | indicates a bar. [B]The stl rhythm is a single line with two beats. The beats are named zak (spoken za) and tuxxu (tu). The beat is stressed as follows:[B]| - x | [B]where x is a beat, - is silent and | indicates a bar. [B]The ospo rhythm is made from two patterns: the nol and the stotho. As stated above, they are to be played in polyrhythm. [B]The nol rhythm is a single line with four beats. The beats are named dab (spoken da), nolsmu (no), agun (ag) and ung (ung). The beat is stressed as follows:[B]| - x - x | [B]where x is a beat, - is silent and | indicates a bar.

The Azure Rhythm is a form of music used during marches and military engagements originating in The Terrors of Muting. The rules of the form are applied by composers to produce individual pieces of music which can be performed. A chanter recites nonsensical words and sounds while the music is played on two orsp and a slet. The musical voices join in melody and counterpoint, harmony and rhythm. The entire performance should feel mysterious. The melody has short phrases, while the counterpoint has long phrases throughout the form. Never more than an interval sounds at once. It is performed in the ulu rhythm. Throughout, when possible, composers and performers are to make trills, play rapid runs and add fills. The voice uses its entire range from the quavering low register to the strident high register. [B]The slet always does the main melody. [B]The Azure Rhythm has a well-defined multi-passage structure: a chorus and a lengthy verse all repeated one times, a bridge-passage and a brief finale. The passage is performed using the xenmu scale. [B]The verse is voiced by the melody of the slet, the counterpoint of the orsp and the rhythm of the chanter reciting nonsensical words and sounds. The passage is fast, and it is to be loud. The slet stays in the crisp low register, each of the orsp covers its entire range from the quavering low register to the strident high register and the chanter's voice stays in the high register. The passage is performed using the ost scale. [B]The bridge-passage is voiced by the melody of the slet and the harmony of the chanter reciting any composition of The Strategy of Poetry. The passage is consistently slowing, and it is to fade into silence. The slet stays in the strident middle register and the chanter's voice covers its entire range. The passage is performed using the odu scale. [B]The finale is voiced by the melody of the orsp and the melody of the slet. The passage is at a free tempo, and it is to become louder and louder. Each of the orsp covers its entire range from the quavering low register to the strident high register and the slet stays in the strident middle register. The passage is performed using the urdu scale. [B]Scales are conceived of as two chords built using a division of the perfect fourth interval into eight notes. The tonic note is a fixed tone passed from teacher to student. [B]As always, the xenmu pentatonic scale is thought of as two disjoint chords drawn from the fundamental division of the perfect fourth. These chords are named ngub and slulasp. [B]The ngub trichord is the 1st, the 5th and the 8th degrees of the fundamental perfect fourth division. [B]The slulasp trichord is the 1st, the 5th and the 8th degrees of the fundamental perfect fourth division. [B]As always, the ost heptatonic scale is thought of as two disjoint chords drawn from the fundamental division of the perfect fourth. These chords are named usnusp and ekxox. [B]The usnusp tetrachord is the 1st, the 3rd, the 6th and the 8th degrees of the fundamental perfect fourth division. [B]The ekxox tetrachord is the 1st, the 3rd, the 6th and the 8th degrees of the fundamental perfect fourth division. [B]As always, the odu hexatonic scale is thought of as two disjoint chords drawn from the fundamental division of the perfect fourth. These chords are named lsm and asmuk. [B]The lsm trichord is the 1st, the 7th and the 8th degrees of the fundamental perfect fourth division. [B]The asmuk tetrachord is the 1st, the 2nd, the 5th and the 8th degrees of the fundamental perfect fourth division. [B]As always, the urdu hexatonic scale is thought of as two disjoint chords drawn from the fundamental division of the perfect fourth. These chords are named usnusp and ozse. [B]The ozse trichord is the 1st, the 7th and the 8th degrees of the fundamental perfect fourth division. [B]The rhythm system is fundamentally polyrhythmic. There are always multiple rhythm lines, and each of their bars is played over the same period of time, regardless of the number of beats. The rhythm lines are thought of as one, without a primary-subordinate relationship, though individual lines can be named. [B]The ulu rhythm is made from two patterns: the ugas and the zudl. [B]The ugas rhythm is a single line with four beats. The beats are named ustrok (spoken us), gosma (go), kbu (k) and ron (ro). The beat is stressed as follows:[B]| - - - x | [B]where x is a beat, - is silent and | indicates a bar. [B]The zudl rhythm is a single line with four beats. The beat is stressed as follows:[B]| x - - - | [B]where x is a beat, - is silent and | indicates a bar.

The Bewildering Luxuries is a devotional form of music originating in The Terrors of Muting. The rules of the form are applied by composers to produce individual pieces of music which can be performed. A speaker recites nonsensical words and sounds while the music is played on a slole and a zok. The music is melody and rhythm without harmony. The entire performance is to be in whispered undertones. It is performed using the nuklat scale and in free rhythm. [B]The speaker always should bring a sense of motion. [B]The slole always provides the rhythm and should bring a sense of motion. [B]The zok always does the main melody, should perform expressively and glides from note to note. [B]The Bewildering Luxuries has a well-defined multi-passage structure: an introduction and a passage and another one to two passages. [B]The introduction is at a hurried pace. The zok ranges from the raucous low register to the wispy middle register. The passage has mid-length phrases in the melody. This passage features only melodic tones and intervals. [B]The first simple passage is very slow. The zok ranges from the raucous low register to the wispy middle register. The passage has long phrases in the melody. This passage typically has some sparse chords. [B]Each of the second simple passages is fast. The zok covers its entire range from the raucous low register to the sparkling high register. Each passage has mid-length phrases in the melody. This passage typically has some sparse chords. [B]Scales are conceived of as two chords built using a division of the perfect fourth interval into eight notes. The tonic note is a fixed tone passed from teacher to student. [B]As always, the nuklat heptatonic scale is thought of as two disjoint chords drawn from the fundamental division of the perfect fourth. These chords are named ogo and ok. [B]The ogo tetrachord is the 1st, the 3rd, the 4th and the 8th degrees of the fundamental perfect fourth division. [B]The ok tetrachord is the 1st, the 3rd, the 4th and the 8th degrees of the fundamental perfect fourth division.
